-- MTN Will Pay Outgoing CEO $4.3 Million to Stay Away From Telecoms Industry
-- Nicky Smith
-- 2010-07-16T15:48:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-16/mtn-will-pay-outgoing-ceo-4-3-million-to-stay-away-from-telecoms-industry.html

          
          
             MTN Group Ltd. , Africa’s largest
mobile phone operator, will pay Chief Executive Officer
 Phuthuma Nhleko  33 million rand ($4.35 million) as part of two
restraint of trade agreements as he leaves at the end of March.  
 Neither Nhleko, nor any company in which he has an
interest, is allowed solicit or canvass for mobile
telecommunications business in any territories where MTN does
business, under the three-year restriction, according to a
statement on the company’s  website .  
 Nhleko, 50, who has headed the company for the past eight
years, said in May he would not renew his contract which
expired in June. He agreed to stay on until March while the
board seeks a successor. MTN operates across  21 countries .  
 According to  Bloomberg data , Nhleko holds 3.35 million MTN
shares, making his stake worth about 392 million rand with the
stock closing at 116.96 rand at 5 p.m. in Johannesburg.  
 Nhleko was paid 14.7 million rand in salary and bonuses
for the year ended June 2009, down from 19.5 million a year
earlier.  
